{{about|the BASIC-like programming language|the Forth-like programming language "LSE"|STOIC}}
'''LSE''' ({{lang-fr|Langage symbolique d'enseignement}}) is a [[programming language]] developed at [[Supélec]] in the late 1970s/early 1980s.<ref name="Hebenstreit2006">{{cite book|last=Hebenstreit|first=Jacques|editor=Jacquetta Megarry|title=World Yearbook of Education 1982/3: Computers and Education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VeXYAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA126|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-16772-0|page=126|chapter=The '10,000 microcomputers plan' in France|quote=The language LSE (Langage Symbolique d'Enseignement–a symbolic teaching language) was defined at my laboratory in 1971 and implemented on the MITRA 15 and T1600, both French-made systems.}}</ref><ref name="Marquet2004">{{cite book|author=Pascal Marquet|title=Informatique et enseignement: progrès ou évolution?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aeK6lBSoJAMC&pg=PA19|year=2004|publisher=Editions Mardaga|language=fr|isbn=978-2-87009-875-2|page=19}}</ref><ref name="Schmucler1997">{{cite book|author=Héctor Schmucler|title=Memoria de la comunicación|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mKPfXxDcih4C&pg=PA178|year=1997|publisher=Editorial Biblos|language=es|isbn=978-950-786-141-3|page=178}}</ref> It is similar to [[BASIC]], except with [[French language|French]]-language instead of [[English language|English]]-language keywords. It was derived from an earlier language called ''LSD'', also developed at Supélec. It is most commonly said to be an acronym for ''Langage Symbolique d'Enseignement'' (Symbolic Teaching Language), but other expansions are also known (e.g. ''Langage de Sup-Élec'', or the more cynical ''Langage Sans Espoir'' (hopeless language)).
It originally flourished due to support from the [[Ministry of National Education (France)|French Ministry of National Education]], but declined as the ministry lost interest. It went through a number of revisions; earlier versions of LSE lacked full support for [[structured programming]], which later version added, along with [[exception handling]].
